Any worry that Ronaldo, now 33, was going gently into that good night was quelled by his incendiary past 12 months. Don’t believe us? He vaulted Real Madrid to their first La Liga title since 2012 and third Champions League title in four seasons. He equaled Messi’s record five Ballon d’Or trophies. Not to mention, Ronaldo is the Champions League's all-time leading scorer (120), 20 ahead of Messi and nearly 50 ahead of third-place Raul. His earth-shattering bicycle kick against Juventus this spring had former teammate Alvaro Arbeloa declaring that CR7 should start playing against Martians instead. Interstellar competition notwithstanding, Ronaldo belongs on the summit. -- Dan Hajducky

There are people out there who hate me and who say I’m arrogant, vain and whatever. That’s all part of my success. I am made to be the best.

Ronaldo

On statistics alone, AB de Villiers is the second-best one-day batsman in the world, but there is a wonderful, well-natured competitiveness between him and Virat Kohli, who sits atop of the rankings. They are the Federer-Nadal of cricket. But it was his return to the Test arena that has made his 2017 truly remarkable. Having sat out for two years -- through injury and a sabbatical, where he played the white-ball version of the sport -- de Villiers returned to the Test team in December and promptly captained South Africa to a win over Zimbabwe. He then finished top run-scorer in the series against India, no longer doubling up as wicket keeper as his back could no longer take the strain. And then came the century against Australia in March, his first since January 2015. The fire had returned to De Villiers having taken time out to breathe, and he has sights set on featuring in next year’s World Cup. -- Tom Hamilton

AB and Federer share a similar DNA, I think, and the same with Nadal and Kohli. The point’s never dead for Nadal, and the point’s never dead for Virat. And AB, he finds a way, as Federer does, in conditions where others struggle.

Royal Challengers Bangalore coach Trent Woodhill

Sania Mirza has seen the good -- and bad -- sides of fame. When she started out, she was endeavoring to become the first Muslim woman to play tennis professionally in India. This meant dealing with relentless criticism: Her tennis skirt was too small, she had too much makeup on, she was too career-oriented. Despite it all, she succeeded on the court and off. She was named United Nations Women’s Goodwill Ambassador for South Asia and, in 2016, was named in Time’s 100 Most Influential People in the world list. Mirza is attracting more attention than ever with the announcement of her pregnancy with husband and former Pakistani cricket captain, Shoaib Malik. -- Aishwarya Kumar

When I go out on court, I don’t care what I look like. It doesn’t matter what I’m wearing, it doesn’t matter what I look, it doesn’t matter what my hair feels like. All I feel is the moment I have to play well, give my 100 percent and win the match.

To find the 100 most famous athletes in the world, we started with 600 of the biggest names in sports, drawn from 68 countries. ESPN's Sports Analytics Group then ranked them based on a proprietary formula that took into account three fame factors:

1

Search Score

Which measures how often a name is searched, using Cristiano Ronaldo's score of 100 as a baseline

2

Endorsements Dollars

Our sources ranged from Forbes to ESPN contributors such as Darren Rovell

3

Social Media Followers

Since not all athletes are on every platform, we used only the number from their most popular account. So if an athlete had 2 million Instagram followers but his or her other accounts had only 1 million followers, the social media score was 2 million.

Easy, right? Now for the fine print: If we could not find accurate endorsement figures, we estimated an athlete's endorsement dollars based on the search, social and endorsement data for all athletes under review; for Chinese athletes, we used the Baidu search score and the Weibo social numbers because Google and Western social platforms have been blocked in China.

If an athlete had no confirmed social media account, we marked a "0" for social media. Our deadline for all underlying metrics was March 19; the currency conversions were done by that date.
